<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900801-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>900801-0011.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>08/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   A U.S. PANEL cleared the first human tests of gene therapyto fight disease.   The National Institutes of Health committee approved theuse of gene therapy to treat a fatal form of skin cancer andan inherited immune-system disorder that affects children.The panel's chairman said that the approvals move genetherapy &quot;from abstract science to research and patient care.&quot;Scientists have traced some inherited disorders, includinghemophilia and cystic fibrosis, to malfunctions by genes,which instruct cells to perform functions. As a result,researchers are focusing on therapies to replace missinggenes or to enhance the genes' performance as a possibletreatment for disease.</LP><TEXT>   But gene therapy has attracted criticism from groups whoworry that it could lead to tinkering with genetic structuresto improve the human race.   ---   AN OIL SPILL SPREAD off Texas, disrupting shipping andthreatening wildlife.   The spill from a collision between a tanker and two bargesin Galveston Bay blocked most vessels for the third day fromthe Houston Ship Channel, though some ships went through lastnight. The Coast Guard said only a few dead birds and fishwere reported, but that more were expected as the oil movedashore. Initially, Coast Guard officials said only about50,000 gallons of oil spilled, but they later raised that to500,000 gallons.   Local maritime shipping experts estimated that theshipping channel's closing is costing $1 million to $1.5million a day to owners of idled ships.   ---   A defense spending bill was approved by the House ArmedServices panel that guts the Pentagon's top-prioritystrategic programs, shelves production of other weapons andcuts three times as many troops as Bush proposed. In clearingthe $283 billion bill, the panel cut $24 billion from Bush'sspending blueprint.   ---   Scientists said they are on the trail of a gene thatraises the risk of developing lung cancer, especially forsmokers. Two research reports are the firmest proof yet thata susceptibility to lung cancer can be passed from generationto generation, and may explain why lung cancer is relativelycommon in some families.   ---   Moslem rebels freed Trinidad's Prime Minister Robinson,but other hostages seized during Friday's coup attempt werestill being held, according to Trinidad's attorney general.He refused to say what conditions led to Robinson's release.According to other officials, the premier had been shot inboth legs and beaten during his captivity.   ---   Federal investigators spread blame for the March 1989Exxon Valdez oil spill off Alaska, criticizing the captain,his third mate, the Coast Guard and state and localauthorities, as well as Exxon Shipping. The NationalTransportation Safety Board's findings ended a 16-month probeconcerning the nation's worst spill.   ---   Liberian government troops staged a counterattack onrebels fighting to oust Doe and recaptured parts of Monrovia.Meanwhile, the president vowed to &quot;fight until the lastsoldiers in the Liberian army die.&quot; The offensive came a dayafter loyalist troops were accused of killing hundreds ofcivilian refugees in a Lutheran church.   ---   A Senate subcommittee rejected fiscal 1991 funding soughtby the Bush administration to establish a National DrugIntelligence Center under the Justice Department and drugczar Bennett. Instead, the Appropriations panel chose toapply the requested $46 million to expand an existinganti-drug program.   ---   The Irish Republican Army said in a statement that itkilled British lawmaker Ian Gow because of his friendshipwith Prime Minister Thatcher and his role in developingBritain's policy concerning Northern Ireland. Gow, 53, diedMonday when a bomb exploded under his automobile.   ---   Kuwaiti and Iraqi negotiators began talks in Saudi Arabiaon their oil and border dispute, while Persian Gulf-baseddiplomats said Iraq had massed 100,000 troops on Kuwait'sborder. The diplomats said the Iraqi force, triple the numberearlier reported, included about 300 Soviet-made tanks.   ---   A federal jury in Los Angeles found a Mexican businessmanguilty of racketeering, kidnapping and conspiracy in the 1985death of U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena. Ruben Zuno Arce, abrother-in-law of a former president of Mexico, was the thirddefendant found guilty in the trial.   ---   Soviet citizens will be allowed, as of today, to spend andsave convertible currency without stating the source of theincome. The government also plans to open stores sellingcertain imported and domestic goods for hard currency.</TEXT></DOC>